observations.recommendation:
We recommended to the management to do the following:

Organize an Inventory Committee which shall have at least one member from the Accounting Office and one member from the General Services Office (GSO);
Prepare a Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) through the Inventory Committee containing the following information:

The specific assignments/duties of the Committee members.
The cut-off date for the inventory.
Schedule specifying the dates and locations of the inventory taking activities from start up to the targeted completion of the physical inventory which must be in three months or less.
Conduct the physical inventory taking together with a representative of the Commission in Audit (COA) as witness;
Prepare a Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System and Road Map, and provide copies to the Accounting Office and GSO;
Provide the complete description, cost segregation, useful life, rate of depreciation for each local road and depreciable road component in coordination with the Accounting Office and Engineering Office;
Maintain a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and road components at the GSO;
Maintain subsidiary ledgers and Local Road Network Ledger Card for each local road and road components at the Accounting Office;
Submit to the COA Office a Report on Local Road Network to be prepared by the GSO at year-end;
Submit to the COA Office a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each road component at year-end; and
Disclose the total road network system in the Notes to the Financial Statements of the LGU at year-end.

We recommended the management to:

a. Submit a copy of Ordinances, Resolutions or any legal basis for the implementation of the Housing/Resettlement Projects;
b. Direct the Municipal Accountant to set-up the Special Account in the General Fund – Housing to record transactions related thereto;
c. Clarify with the Province if the collections from Kibawe Village still needs to be remitted to the latter;
d. Direct the Municipal Engineer or the MPDO (whichever is the proper office) to submit the project details for each project in order for the Accounting Office to record the cost related to the projects;
e. Direct the MACCO, MEDO, and MTO to reconcile its records in order to provide accurate data of collections and balances;
f. Direct the Municipal Accountant, after determination of the cost of the house and lot and residential lots held for sale by the municipality and after determination of correct total collections, to make the necessary adjusting entries (supported with documents) to correct the financial statements;
g. Direct the MEEDO provide the contract cost for the projects at the Kibawe Village in order for the municipality to determine the remaining liability to the Province (of collections is to be remitted to the latter);
h. Direct the MEEDO, as the office in-charge for the project, to keep copies of contract for each buyer, details as to the development cost of the residential lots and construction cost of the housing units, and should also keep copy of the Ordinances or resolutions relating to the project.

We recommended to the management to require the Officer in charge of the Municipal Accountant’s Office to do the following:

Request the Provincial Project Monitoring and Inspection Team to inspect the project Construction of Kibawe Market Stall Building (Phase 1) and secure inspection report therefrom. Submit the inspection report to the Provincial Accountant’s Office for it to recognize and record the liquidation of LGU Kibawe;

Confirm the balance of the reciprocal Due from LGU account in the books of the PGB and reconcile both records to identify and address, if not eliminate, the noted discrepancies; and 

Subsequently, facilitate the regular reconciliation with the PGB records for proper and correct presentation and reporting of balances;

We recommended to the management to do the following courses of action:

The Acting Municipal Treasurer must return the unutilized PDAFs and must immediately issue a check payable to the Bureau of the Treasury amounted to ₱ 170,470.35;

The Acting Municipal Accountant must prepare a corresponding Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to adjust the “Other Payables” account once the PDAFs are already returned to the Bureau of the Treasury.

